rmingling influences of Yoruba and Classical Greek mythologies in Brazilian representations of the carnivalesque Black Orpheus, while his analysis of City of God focuses on the growing centrality of the ghetto, or favela, as a theme and producer of culture in the early twenty-first-century Brazilian urban scene. Ultimately, Afolabi argues, the identities of these figures are not fixed, but rather inhabit a fluid terrain of ideological and political struggle, challenging the idealistic notion that racial hybridity has eliminated racial discrimination in Brazil.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Mrz 2024) 0aBlacks in literature. 0aBlacksxRace identityzBrazil. 0aBrazilian literaturexHistory and criticism. 0aRace in literature. 4aAfrican American Studies : Black Studies. 4aCultural Studies : Cultural Studies. 4aCultural Studies : Postcolonial Studies. 4aHistory : History. 4aLatin American, Caribbean, and Latinx Studies : Latin American Studies. 4aLiterature : Literature. 7aHISTORY / Latin America / South America.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2021z978311149169140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143848251440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438482514423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438482514/original  a978-3-11-149169-1  SUNY Press eBook Package 2021b2021  aGBV-deGruyter-alles